This is a known breaking change in **.NET MAUI 10**. Android 15 enforces **edge-to-edge** rendering, and `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` was fully removed. MAUI 10 adopted edge-to-edge by default, so the old API no longer works.

## The Fix

**1. Keep `adjustResize` in your `AndroidManifest.xml`** (it still signals intent to the system):

```xml
<activity
    ...
    android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" />
```

**2. Use MAUI's built-in edge-to-edge inset handling.** Your page content automatically gets padded for the keyboard *if* you use a resizable layout. A `Grid` with your input bar at the bottom works well:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">

        <!-- Chat messages -->
        <CollectionView Grid.Row="0"
                        ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}"
                        ItemsUpdatingScrollMode="KeepLastItemInView">
            <!-- your item template -->
        </CollectionView>

        <!-- Input bar -->
        <Grid Grid.Row="1" ColumnDefinitions="*, Auto" Padding="8">
            <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." />
            <Button Grid.Column="1" Text="Send" />
        </Grid>

    </Grid>
</ContentPage>
```

**3. If it's still hidden**, the edge-to-edge system may not be propagating IME insets to your root layout. Add this platform-specific code in your `MainActivity.cs` or a custom handler:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
using Android.OS;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Ensure the decor view reacts to IME (keyboard) insets
        if (Window?.DecorView is Android.Views.View decorView)
        {
            ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(decorView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
        }
    }

    private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var systemBars = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());

            // Apply bottom padding = max of keyboard or nav bar
            v.SetPadding(
                systemBars.Left,
                systemBars.Top,
                systemBars.Right,
                Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, systemBars.Bottom));

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

## Summary

| .NET 9 | .NET 10 |
|---|---|
| `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` | Edge-to-edge + `WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()` |

The key insight: the keyboard is now just another **window inset** (like the status bar or nav bar). The framework handles it automatically in most cases — step 3 is only needed if auto-handling doesn't reach your specific layout.
